==Latin==
{{wikipedia|lang=la}}
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|la|grc|Χ|t=chi}}, which represented /ks/ in the dialects of most of the Greek mainland and Euboea.
===Pronunciation===
The sound of X was like that of the Greek {{m|el|Ξ|t=xi}}, that is /ks/, although etymologically it represented not only ''cs'' (as in {{l|la|lūx}}, from luc-s, and {{l|la|dīxī}}, from dic-si), but also ''gs'' (as in {{l|la|lēx}}, from leg-s; {{l|la|rēxī}}, from reg-si); ''hs'' (as in {{l|la|trāxī}}, from trah-si; {{l|la|vexī}}, from veh-si); and ''chs'' (as in the word {{l|la|onyx}}, from onych-s, borrowed from the Greek). The
hardening of a softer final (''g'', ''h'', ''ch'') before ''s'' into the ''с'' sound, which occurs in the last-mentioned cases, is found also in several roots ending in ''v'' and ''u'': {{l|la|nix}} for niv-s, {{l|la|vīxī}} for viv-si, {{l|la|connixī}} for conniv-si, {{l|la|fluxī}} for fluv-si, from {{l|la|fluō}} (root fluv; cf. {{l|la|fluvius}}), {{l|la|struxī}} for stru-si. Less frequently ''x'' has arisen from the combinations ''ps'' and ''ts'': {{l|la|proximus}} for prop-simus (from {{l|la|prope}}), {{l|la|nīxus}} for nit-sus (from {{l|la|nītor}}), the latter being used along with the collateral form {{l|la|nīsus}}, as also {{l|la|connīvī}} with {{l|la|connixī}}, and {{l|la|mistus}} (from {{l|la|misceō}}) with {{l|la|mixtus}}. An
exchange of the sounds ''ss'' or ''s'' and ''x'', took place in {{l|la|axis}} for assis and {{l|la|laxus}} for lassus. In the later language of the vulgar, the guttural sound in ''x'' disappeared, and ''s'' or ''ss'' was often written for it; as vis for {{l|la|vix}}, visit for {{l|la|vīxit}}, unsit for {{l|la|unxit}}, conflississet for {{l|la|conflixisset}}, in late inscriptions; hence regularly in Italian, and frequently in the other Romance tongues, the Latin ''x'' is represented by ''s'' or ''ss''.
By a mere graphic variation, one of the constituent sounds of ''x'' is often expressed in inscriptions (but not the earliest) by an additional ''с'' or ''s''; as SACXO or SAXSO for {{l|la|saxō}}; VCXOR or VXSOR for {{l|la|uxor}}; CONIVNCX or CONIVNXS for {{l|la|conjunx}}; even both sounds are sometimes thus expressed, VICXSIT for {{l|la|vīxit}}.
===Letter===
{{la-letter|upper=X|lower=x}}
# {{Latn-def|la|letter|23}}
===Numeral===
{{head|la|numeral}}
# {{cln|la|cardinal numbers}} {{l|en|ten}}; ''{{l|la|decem}}''.
====See also====
* Roman numeral letters: {{l|la|I}}, {{l|la|V}}, {{l|la|L}}, {{l|la|C}}, {{l|la|D}}, {{l|la|M}}.
* Unicode glyphs of Roman numerals: [[Ⅹ]], [[ⅹ]].
* Appendixes: [[Appendix:Roman numerals|Roman numerals]], [[Appendix:Latin cardinal numerals|Latin cardinal numerals]]
===References===
* “X” in Charlton T. Lewis and Charles Short [1907], ''A New Latin Dictionary''.
