==German==
{{wikipedia|lang=de}}
===Alternative forms===
* {{alt|de|Santen||obsolete}}
===Etymology===
From {{inh|de|gmh|Santen|Sante(n)}}, from {{der|de|la|Sanctos|lit=(at) the saints}}. The spelling with initial ''X-'' first appears in Latin texts of the 10th century. One theory links it with {{der|de|grc|Ξάνθος}}, the gods’ name for the {{w|Karamenderes River|Scamander}} river near [[Troy]] according to the {{w|Iliad}}. This theory is based on the fact that there was indeed a well-attested mediaeval legend equating Xanten with Troy. The inherited local pronunciation is {{m|de||Santen}} /ˈsan.tən/, but it has now been widely displaced by the {{spelling pronunciation|de|nocap=1}}. {{m|de||Xanten}} is the only German locality in ''X-'' (though there are a few Bavarian ones in ''Gs-'', also pronounced with {{IPAchar|/ks/}}).
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|de|/ˈksan.tən/}}
* {{audio|de|De-Xanten.ogg|Audio}}
===Proper noun===
{{de-proper noun|toponym}}
# {{place|de|town|r/{{w|Lower Rhine region|Lower Rhine}}|s/North Rhine-Westphalia|c/Germany|t=Xanten}}
===References===
* Hawicks, Heike: ''Sanctos–Xantum–Troia – Zum Einfluss ottonisch-byzantinischer Beziehungen auf die Toponymie im Xantener Raum'', in: Ludwig, Uwe & Schilp, Thomas (editors): Mittelalter an Rhein und Maas – Beiträge zur Geschichte des Niederrheins, Waxmann Verlag, 2004, p. 27-41.

==English==
===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|fr|xantheine}}, apparently an arbitrary respelling to distinguish it from the similarly spelled {{m|fr|xanthine}}. Ultimately from {{uder|en|grc|-}}; see {{m|en|xanthine}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈzænθiːn/}}
* {{homophones|en|xanthene|xanthine}}
===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}
# {{lb|en|chemistry}} The water-soluble part of the yellow [[carotenoid]] pigment present in the cell [[sap]] of some plants.
====Usage notes====
* ''Xanthein'' and similar-sounding words have also been used for several different yellow compounds derived from plants.
====Synonyms====
* {{l|en|xanthin}}
* {{l|en|xanthine}}
====Translations====
