==English==
===Etymology===
Coined by Ivor Darreg, from {{prefix|en|xeno|harmonic|alt1=xen-}}
===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}
{{wikipedia|Xenharmonic music}}
# {{lb|en|music}} Not conforming to the common 12-tone equal temperament.
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=A Xenharmonist's Message to the Computer Musicians|author=Ivor Darreg|volume=2|issue=2|date=September 1978|publisher=The MIT Press|journal=Computer Music Journal|passage=The back cover lists "Materials and Services", including ''Xenharmonikon'' (cooperation prevails in the '''xenharmonic''' world), and persons cooperating in a tape exchange--meaning that if you send a tape of your music, to someone on the list, you get back a tape of their music.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Tuning, Timbre, Spectrum, Scale|page=189|author=William A. Sethares|year=2013|passage=Dissonance scores can also be applied in situations where no musical score exists, and two examples are given: a '''xenharmonic''' piece by Carlos, and a Balinese gamelan performance.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z5XxBwAAQBAJ&lpg=PA189&dq=%22a%20xenharmonic%22&pg=PA189#v=onepage&q=%22a%20xenharmonic%22&f=false}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Composing Electronic Music: A New Aesthetic|page=219|author=Curtis Roads|year=2015|passage=Microtonal music is sometimes referred to as '''''xenharmonic''''' music, the term deriving from the Greek ''xenia'' (hospitable) and ''xenos'' (foreign or strange) (Chalmers 1974; Darreg 1977; Wilson 2014).|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Zs_CQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA219&dq=%22xenharmonic%22%20Ivor%20Darreg&pg=PA219#v=onepage&q=%22xenharmonic%22%20Ivor%20Darreg&f=false}}
====Synonyms====
* {{l|en|microtonal}}

