{{also|Xavér}}
==German==
===Etymology===
From {{bor|de|es|Xavier}} (older spelling of {{m|es|Javier}}), after 16th-century Catholic saint {{w|Francis Xavier}}.
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|de|/ˈksaːvər/|[ˈksaː.vɐ]}}
* {{audio|de|De-Xaver.ogg|Audio}}
===Proper noun===
{{de-proper noun|m,s:-[with an article]}}
# {{given name|de|male|eq=Xavier}}
====Usage notes====
* Often combined with {{m|de|Franz}} as {{m|de||Franz Xaver}} or {{m|de|Franz-Xaver}}.
* The name has traditionally been restricted by sect as well as region, namely to Catholics (Francis Xavier being a leading figure of the {{w|Counter-Reformation}}), and mostly to [[Upper German]] (i.e. southern) areas, where initial {{IPAchar|/ks/}} (spelt ''gs-'') is a usual onset in the local dialects and thus poses no phonetic difficulty. It is most common in [[Bavaria]] and [[Austria]].

